  "prompt": "I'm a US citizen and my boyfriend is Argentinean; if we get married in the US, how long will it take for him to be qualified to work in the US?",
  "response": "If you marry your boyfriend in the United States, he will need to go through several steps to become qualified to work in the US. Here is a general overview of the process:\n\n1. **Marriage and Adjustment of Status (AOS):** After getting married, you can file Form I-130 (Petition for Alien Relative) and Form I-485 (Application to Register Permanent Residence or Adjust Status) concurrently. This starts the process for him to become a lawful permanent resident (green card holder).\n\n2. **Employment Authorization Document (EAD):** While his I-485 application is pending, he can apply for an Employment Authorization Document (EAD) by filing Form I-765. This allows him to work legally in the US while waiting for his green card. Usually, the EAD is processed within 3 to 6 months after filing.\n\n3. **Advance Parole:** Additionally, he can apply for Advance Parole (Form I-131) allowing him to travel outside the US while his AOS application is pending.\n\n4. **Biometrics Appointment:** He will be scheduled for a biometrics appointment where his fingerprints, photo, and signature will be collected.\n\n5. **Interview:** Both of you will be required to attend an interview at a USCIS office. This is typically scheduled within several months after filing the applications.\n\n6. **Approval and Green Card:** If the interview goes well and his application is approved, he will receive a green card. The entire process from filing to receiving the green card can take anywhere from 10 months to over a year, depending on various factors like USCIS processing times and the specifics of your case.\n\nOnce he receives his EAD, he can legally work in the US while waiting for his green card. After obtaining the green card, he will have permanent resident status and can work freely without the need for an EAD.\n\nIt's important to note that processing times can vary, and it is advisable to consult with an immigration attorney to ensure that all forms are correctly filled out and to receive guidance specific to your case.",
